# Analysis: Why the image from PR #555 didn't appear in the 0.21.0 release changelog

## Root Cause

The image was stored as a **standalone HTML `<img>` tag** in the raw PR body (confirmed via `gh api repos/getsentry/cli/pulls/555 --jq '.body'`):

```html
<img
  width="2512"
  height="1757"
  alt="image"
  src="https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/..."
/>
```

GitHub's web UI renders uploaded images with the `![image](url)` markdown syntax visually, but internally stores them as `<img>` HTML tags. When `marked.lexer()` parses this, it produces a token of type `html` — not `paragraph`.

Craft's `parseTokensToEntries()` function (`src/utils/changelog.ts:384-435`) only handles three token types:

- `list`
- `paragraph`
- `code`

**All other token types (including `html`) are silently dropped.** So the image was collected from the `## Changelog Entry` section but discarded during token-to-entry conversion.

### Verification

```bash
# Raw PR body has HTML img, not markdown image:
gh api repos/getsentry/cli/pulls/555 --jq '.body' | head -10
```

```javascript
// marked tokenizes standalone <img> as type 'html', which is dropped:
const tokens = marked.lexer('<img src="url" />');
// → [{ type: 'html', raw: '<img src="url" />\n' }]
```

## Proposed Fix

Add an `html` token handler in `parseTokensToEntries()` that preserves HTML blocks (like `<img>` tags) as nested content on the previous entry, similar to how `code` blocks are handled.

### File to modify

- `src/utils/changelog.ts` — `parseTokensToEntries()` function, lines 384-435

### Implementation

After the `code` block handler (line 431), add an `html` token handler:

```typescript
} else if (token.type === 'html') {
  // HTML blocks (e.g., <img> tags from GitHub image uploads) become
  // nested content on the previous entry, similar to code blocks.
  const htmlContent = (token as Tokens.HTML).raw.trim();
  if (htmlContent && entries.length > 0) {
    const prev = entries[entries.length - 1];
    prev.nestedContent = prev.nestedContent
      ? `${prev.nestedContent}\n  ${htmlContent}`
      : `  ${htmlContent}`;
  }
  // If no previous entry exists, skip — an orphaned HTML block
  // without descriptive text isn't a meaningful changelog entry.
}
```

This way, if someone has:

```markdown
## Changelog Entry

Description of the change
<img src="screenshot.png" />
```

The image becomes nested content under "Description of the change" rather than being silently dropped.

### Testing

- Add test cases to `src/__tests__/changelog.test.ts` for:
  1. `<img>` tag after a paragraph in `## Changelog Entry` → preserved as nestedContent
  2. `<img>` tag after a list item → preserved as nestedContent
  3. Standalone `<img>` with no preceding entry → dropped (same as orphaned code blocks)
  4. Inline `<img>` within a paragraph → already preserved (no change needed)

